{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2b74a6c6-9189-4586-a1a5-04fa9b4d1d11","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available in the image, use `kubectl cp` to copy a self-contained `dotnet-trace` binary in, or run it as a sidecar.\n- Add `--format speedscope` to get a JSON file you can open directly in Speedscope (no Windows tooling needed).\n- For lower-level OS + runtime data, use **`dotnet-collect`** with `perf` or **`perfcollect`**, but `dotnet-trace` is the simplest starting point.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ce4fff11-b396-4493-8fca-d2c78cc18712","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":320},"id":"aaf7a985-00b4-4956-b70f-b0962f6781ee","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:54:46.573Z","parentId":"8e7a28a2-3da3-4c03-9d57-c42655bd6562"}
